  "distance": "307.236 km (190.908 miles)",
  "event_preview": "Circuit de Barcelona-Catalunya measures 4.657 km (2.895 mi) and features 14 turns in Montmeló, just outside Barcelona, Spain. Built in 1991 and designed by Hermann Tilke, the circuit has been a fixture on the Formula 1 calendar ever since, also serving as one of the sport's primary pre-season testing venues thanks to its Mediterranean climate and comprehensive layout. The track demands a true all-round car — a mixture of high-speed sweepers, heavy braking zones and technical low-speed corners makes it nearly impossible to optimise a setup for every sector simultaneously. For 2023 the final chicane was removed in favour of the original fast sweeping complex through Turns 13–14, restoring some of the circuit's character. The 2025 Spanish Grand Prix carries additional poignancy as the last Formula 1 race to be held at this venue — from 2026, the race moves to a new purpose-built circuit in Madrid. The official race lap record stands at 1:16.330, set by Max Verstappen for Red Bull during the 2023 Spanish Grand Prix, while the all-time qualifying lap record belongs to Lando Norris, who clocked a 1:11.383 for McLaren in Q3 of the 2024 weekend.",
